#: Game.Levels.FinsetConstructors.L06_DecidableEq
msgid "This worked because §0 has a §1 instance. When we wrote\n"
"§2 in the definition of §3, Lean automatically\n"
"generated a function that can compare any two §4 values for equality.\n"
"\n"
"## What would fail without §5\n"
"\n"
"If we had defined §6 without §7:\n"
"\n"
"§8\n"
"\n"
"Then writing §9 would give:\n"
"\n"
"§10\n"
"\n"
"The §11 operation cannot function without the ability to check\n"
"whether an element is already present.\n"
"\n"
"## Why this matters\n"
"\n"
"For all the types you will encounter in this course -- §12, §13,\n"
"§14, §15, product types, etc. -- §16 is available\n"
"automatically. But when you define your own types, you need to either\n"
"derive it or provide it manually.\n"
"\n"
"## The connection to §17\n"
"\n"
"Recall that a §18 is a pair: a §19 together with a proof\n"
"of §20. The §21 instance is needed not for the multiset\n"
"itself, but for the operations that **maintain** the no-duplicates\n"
"invariant. Without it, §22 cannot check whether the element is\n"
"already present.\n"
"\n"
"**In plain language**: \"To build a finite set, you need to be able to\n"
"check whether two elements are equal. For natural numbers and most\n"
"concrete types, this is automatic. For abstract types, you must ensure\n"
"the capability exists.\""
msgstr ""

