#: Game.Levels.FinsetOperations.L08_ByCasesMembership
msgid "# The §0 tactic\n"
"\n"
"Sometimes you need to reason about whether an element **is** or\n"
"**is not** in a finset, without knowing which. The §1 tactic\n"
"splits the proof into two cases.\n"
"\n"
"## Syntax\n"
"\n"
"§2\n"
"\n"
"This creates two goals:\n"
"- In the first, you have §3 (the element is in the finset).\n"
"- In the second, you have §4 (the element is not in the finset).\n"
"\n"
"## Why this works\n"
"\n"
"For finsets, membership is **decidable**: Lean can determine (in\n"
"principle) whether any element belongs to a finset. The §5\n"
"tactic exploits this decidability.\n"
"\n"
"## Your task\n"
"\n"
"Prove that for any finsets §6 and §7, the set difference §8\n"
"is a subset of §9. In other words: removing elements never adds\n"
"new ones.\n"
"\n"
"**Strategy**: Introduce §10 and §11. Rewrite §12 with\n"
"§13 to learn that §14. Extract the first\n"
"component.\n"
"\n"
"Actually, for this level you do NOT need §15 -- this is a\n"
"warm-up. But the next level will use it.\n"
"\n"
"Wait -- let's make this level actually use §16. Here is a\n"
"better task:\n"
"\n"
"Prove that §17. This says: every element of §18 is\n"
"either in the part of §19 outside §20, or in §21 itself.\n"
"\n"
"**Strategy**: Introduce §22 and §23. Use §24\n"
"to split on whether §25 is in §26. If yes, take the right branch of\n"
"the union. If no, take the left branch and use §27."
msgstr ""

