#: Game.Levels.ListBasics.L11_Boss
msgid "Congratulations on completing the Lists world!\n"
"\n"
"You proved that mapping and then filtering preserves membership (for\n"
"elements satisfying the predicate). This required decomposing the problem\n"
"into layers:\n"
"\n"
"1. **Filter layer**: §0 means\n"
"   §1 **and** §2\n"
"2. **Map layer**: §3 means there exists some §4\n"
"   with §5\n"
"3. **Witness**: the element §6 itself, with §7 and §8\n"
"4. **Predicate**: §9 from hypothesis §10\n"
"\n"
"Each layer used a lemma you learned earlier in this world. The boss\n"
"integrates them into a single coherent proof.\n"
"\n"
"## What you learned in this world\n"
"\n"
"1. **List constructors**: §11 is the empty list, §12 prepends §13 to §14,\n"
"   and §15 is sugar for §16\n"
"2. **§17**: counts the number of elements. §18\n"
"   unfolds it on a cons cell.\n"
"3. **§19** (written §20): membership defined recursively.\n"
"   §21 unfolds it into §22.\n"
"4. **§23** (written §24): concatenation. §25\n"
"   characterizes membership. §26 gives the length.\n"
"5. **§27**: applies §28 to every element. §29\n"
"   characterizes membership via an existential witness.\n"
"6. **§30**: keeps elements satisfying §31. §32\n"
"   characterizes membership via a conjunction.\n"
"7. **§33**: accesses elements by §34-indexed position.\n"
"8. **§35**: no duplicate elements. §36 unfolds it.\n"
"\n"
"## Transfer to paper proofs\n"
"\n"
"The proof you just wrote says:\n"
"\n"
"\"To show §37 is in the filtered mapped list, we need two things:\n"
"that §38 is in the mapped list (which holds because §39 is in the\n"
"original list, so §40 is the image of an element we started with),\n"
"and that §41 is true (which is given).\"\n"
"\n"
"Each tactic step corresponds to a sentence in this argument.\n"
"\n"
"## What comes next\n"
"\n"
"In the next world, you will learn about **multisets** -- what happens\n"
"when you keep the multiplicities but forget the ordering. The §42\n"
"property you learned in Level 9 is the bridge: a list satisfying §43\n"
"gives rise to a finset without losing information about which elements\n"
"are present. The journey from lists to multisets to finsets is the central\n"
"structural story of this course.\n"
"\n"
"**Permutations preview**: Two lists that contain the same elements in a\n"
"different order are called *permutations* of each other. In the next world,\n"
"§44 formalizes this, and you will see that two lists that are\n"
"permutations give rise to the same multiset."
msgstr ""

