#: Game.Levels.FinCompute.L04_WhenDecideDoesntHelp
msgid "# §0 When You Need Per-Case Reasoning\n"
"\n"
"§1 is convenient, but it treats the entire goal as a single\n"
"computation. Sometimes you need **control over individual cases** ---\n"
"for example, when each case requires a different lemma or rewriting\n"
"step.\n"
"\n"
"## §2 vs §3\n"
"\n"
"- **§4**: One tactic, no follow-up. Best for fully concrete\n"
"  propositions on small finite types.\n"
"- **§5**: Splits into one goal per element. You choose what\n"
"  to do in each case. Essential when per-case reasoning varies.\n"
"\n"
"## Your task\n"
"\n"
"Prove that for every §6, §7 and §8.\n"
"\n"
"This is a conjunction of two linear inequalities. After §9,\n"
"you get four cases, each a concrete arithmetic check. The semicolon\n"
"combinator §10 handles all of them.\n"
"\n"
"Notice that §11 is **disabled** for this level. The point is to\n"
"build your §12 fluency and see how §13 gives you\n"
"control that §14 does not.\n"
"\n"
"**Rule of thumb**:\n"
"- Try §15 first for fully concrete propositions.\n"
"- Use §16 when you need manual reasoning in some cases,\n"
"  or when §17 is too slow.\n"
"- Use §18 + §19 when the property holds for all §20\n"
"  (not just a specific §21)."
msgstr ""

