#: Game.Levels.MultisetHierarchy.L12_NodupConnection
msgid "# The bridge between List.Nodup and Multiset.Nodup\n"
"\n"
"In the Lists world (W3), you learned about §0: the property\n"
"that every element appears at most once. Now you will see its multiset\n"
"counterpart.\n"
"\n"
"## §1\n"
"\n"
"§2 asserts that every element of multiset §3 has\n"
"multiplicity at most 1 -- no duplicates.\n"
"\n"
"## §4\n"
"\n"
"The key connection is:\n"
"\n"
"§5\n"
"\n"
"A coerced list has no duplicate elements as a multiset if and only if it\n"
"has no duplicate elements as a list. This makes sense: coercion only\n"
"forgets order, and §6 does not depend on order.\n"
"\n"
"## §7\n"
"\n"
"§8 removes duplicate elements from a multiset, keeping\n"
"one copy of each distinct element. It is the internal mechanism behind\n"
"§9.\n"
"\n"
"## §10\n"
"\n"
"The relationship between §11 and §12 is:\n"
"\n"
"§13\n"
"\n"
"A §14 is defined as §15. The §16\n"
"field extracts the underlying multiset. So §17 says: the\n"
"underlying multiset of §18 is §19.\n"
"\n"
"## Your task\n"
"\n"
"Prove two things:\n"
"1. The list §20 has §21 as a multiset (connecting back to W3)\n"
"2. The underlying multiset of §22 is §23\n"
"\n"
"For part 1, rewrite with §24 to reduce to §25,\n"
"then use §26.\n"
"\n"
"For part 2, use §27."
msgstr ""

