#: Game.Levels.FinThreeExamples.L01_Enumerate
msgid "# The World of §0\n"
"\n"
"Welcome to the world of §1 --- the type with exactly three elements:\n"
"§2, §3, and §4.\n"
"\n"
"In the previous worlds, you learned what §5 is (a natural number\n"
"bundled with a proof that it is less than §6) and how to compute with\n"
"it (§7, §8, §9). Now we will spend an entire\n"
"world working concretely with a single small type, §10, to build\n"
"your intuition for finite types.\n"
"\n"
"## Why study a specific example?\n"
"\n"
"Abstract understanding of §11 is important, but it is not enough.\n"
"By working exhaustively with §12, you will develop concrete\n"
"intuition: what does a function on a 3-element set look like? What\n"
"does injectivity mean when you can check every pair? What goes wrong\n"
"when you try to map 3 elements onto 4?\n"
"\n"
"This is the mathematical practice of **concretization**: making\n"
"abstract definitions tangible by grounding them in specific, small cases.\n"
"\n"
"## Your task\n"
"\n"
"Prove that every element of §13 is equal to §14, §15, or §16.\n"
"\n"
"Use §17 to pick an arbitrary element, then §18 to\n"
"split into the three cases. In each case, you need to provide the\n"
"correct disjunct. After §19, the goal for the first case\n"
"will be §20. Use §21 to choose the first\n"
"disjunct, then §22."
msgstr ""

