#: Game.Levels.FinIntro.L01_WhatIsFin
msgid "# Welcome to Finite Index Types\n"
"\n"
"In mathematics, we often need to work with **finite index sets** -- the rows\n"
"of a matrix, the terms of a finite sum, the elements of a finite group. In\n"
"Lean 4, §0 is the canonical way to represent a set with exactly §1\n"
"elements. It is used everywhere: as the index type for vectors and matrices,\n"
"as the domain of finite sums (§2), and as the foundation for\n"
"counting arguments. This course will teach you to work with §3 and the\n"
"broader finite-mathematics infrastructure built on top of it.\n"
"\n"
"## What is §4?\n"
"\n"
"§5 is a **subtype** of the natural numbers. An element of §6 is\n"
"a pair: a natural number §7, together with a proof that §8.\n"
"\n"
"In Lean 4, §9 is defined as:\n"
"§10\n"
"\n"
"So §11 contains the numbers §12 -- each bundled with a proof\n"
"that it is less than §13.\n"
"\n"
"## Your first task\n"
"\n"
"Prove that there exists an element §14 of §15 whose value is §16.\n"
"\n"
"To do this, you need to construct a specific element of §17 and show\n"
"its value is §18. Use §19 to provide the element, then\n"
"close the value goal.\n"
"\n"
"The angle-bracket notation §20 is syntactic sugar for the\n"
"constructor §21. The tactic §22 can automatically prove\n"
"simple arithmetic facts like §23."
msgstr ""

