#: Game.Levels.FinsuppWorld.L05_FinsuppTotality
msgid "# §0 Is a Total Function\n"
"\n"
"A common misconception is that a finitely supported function is a\n"
"**partial function** — defined only at the points in its support.\n"
"\n"
"This is wrong. A §1 §2 is a **total function**:\n"
"§3 is defined for *every* §4. The support is merely the\n"
"set of points where §5. Outside the support, §6 returns §7\n"
"— it does not fail to return a value.\n"
"\n"
"## Concretizing the point\n"
"\n"
"Consider §8. Its support is §9.\n"
"But what happens when you evaluate it at §10? It returns §11:\n"
"\n"
"§12\n"
"\n"
"The function is defined at §13. It just happens to be zero there.\n"
"\n"
"## Partial functions vs §14\n"
"\n"
"If you wanted a *truly* partial function in Lean, you would use\n"
"§15 or §16 (the type of partial functions). A\n"
"partial function at an undefined point returns §17, not §18.\n"
"\n"
"A §19 is more like a function that \"defaults to zero.\"\n"
"\n"
"## Your task\n"
"\n"
"Prove two things about §20:\n"
"1. It is defined at §21 and returns §22.\n"
"2. §23 is not in its support.\n"
"\n"
"The first part uses §24 + §25. The second requires\n"
"showing that membership in the support implies nonzero value\n"
"(via §26), which contradicts the value being §27."
msgstr ""

