#: Game.Levels.FinsetConstructors.L07_FinsetVsSet
msgid "# Two kinds of \"set\" in Lean\n"
"\n"
"You may have encountered §0 in Lean before -- it represents an\n"
"arbitrary (possibly infinite) subset of §1. Now you are working with\n"
"§2. They look similar but are **fundamentally different types**.\n"
"\n"
"## The key differences\n"
"\n"
"- **Size**: A §3 can be infinite. A §4 is always finite.\n"
"- **Data**: A §5 is a predicate §6. A §7 carries an\n"
"  explicit list of elements (with no duplicates).\n"
"- **Membership**: In a §8, membership is propositional. In a §9,\n"
"  membership is decidable (computable).\n"
"\n"
"## A common source of confusion\n"
"\n"
"Because both use the §10 notation and §11 syntax, it is easy\n"
"to confuse them. But their lemma libraries are **separate**:\n"
"\n"
"- §12 works on §13\n"
"- §14 works on §15\n"
"\n"
"If you tried to apply §16 to a §17 goal, you would get\n"
"a type error:\n"
"\n"
"§18\n"
"\n"
"The §19 lemma expects §20, but §21 union is a\n"
"different operation on a different type. You must use §22\n"
"instead. Always look for lemmas in the §23 namespace, not §24.\n"
"\n"
"## Your task\n"
"\n"
"Prove that §25 is nonempty as a finset. The definition\n"
"§26 means §27. You can prove it by providing\n"
"a witness with §28 and then proving membership.\n"
"\n"
"The membership goal §29 is a concrete\n"
"decidable proposition."
msgstr ""

