#: Game.Levels.ThreeFiniteness.L02_FintypeContrast
msgid "You used §0 to prove that the universal set of §1 is\n"
"finite. This works because §2 has a §3 instance (which follows\n"
"automatically from its §4 instance).\n"
"\n"
"## Why this matters\n"
"\n"
"This conversion is one-directional in a natural sense:\n"
"\n"
"- **§5 implies §6**: if the type is finite,\n"
"  then certainly the set of all elements is finite.\n"
"- **§7 does NOT give you §8 for free**: knowing\n"
"  the set is finite (a §9) does not hand you the enumeration data\n"
"  that §10 carries.\n"
"\n"
"In practice, §11 is the stronger notion. When you have it, you\n"
"automatically get §12 for §13 and for every subset.\n"
"\n"
"**In plain language**: \"If a type is finite, then its universal set\n"
"is certainly finite. The converse requires more work.\""
msgstr ""

