#: Game.Levels.FinsetSum.L01_WhatIsFinsetSum
msgid "# Big sums over finite sets\n"
"\n"
"Welcome to the **Finset.sum** world! In this world you will learn to\n"
"write and simplify big-sum expressions — the formal version of\n"
"§0.\n"
"\n"
"## The idea\n"
"\n"
"In ordinary mathematics you write\n"
"§1\n"
"\n"
"In Lean 4 / mathlib the same idea is captured by §2:\n"
"\n"
"§3\n"
"\n"
"which means \"add up §4 as §5 ranges over the elements of the\n"
"finset §6.\" There is also a nice notation:\n"
"\n"
"§7\n"
"\n"
"## The type-class requirement\n"
"\n"
"§8 needs the result type to be an §9 — a type\n"
"with §10, §11, and the laws that §12 is associative and commutative\n"
"and §13 is a neutral element. All of §14, §15, §16, and §17\n"
"satisfy this automatically.\n"
"\n"
"## Your first task\n"
"\n"
"Prove that §18.\n"
"\n"
"This is just saying that the sum of a single element is that element\n"
"itself. The lemma §19 handles it:\n"
"\n"
"§20\n"
"\n"
"When the function is the identity (i.e., you sum the elements themselves),\n"
"§21 becomes just §22."
msgstr ""

