#: Game.Levels.ThreeFiniteness.L01_SetFinite
msgid "# Three Notions of Finiteness\n"
"\n"
"In Lean and Mathlib there are *three* different ways to express that\n"
"something is finite:\n"
"\n"
"1. **§0** — a *predicate* on a set (a §1).\n"
"2. **§2** — a *type class* on a type.\n"
"3. **§3** — a *data type* representing a concrete finite collection.\n"
"\n"
"Each serves a different purpose, and knowing when to use which is an\n"
"important skill. This world introduces all three, explains their\n"
"relationships, and shows you how to convert between them.\n"
"\n"
"## §4\n"
"\n"
"Given a set §5, the proposition §6 (or §7)\n"
"asserts that §8 has finitely many elements. It is a *predicate*: it\n"
"lives in §9, and it carries no computational data about what those\n"
"elements are or how to enumerate them.\n"
"\n"
"## Key lemmas\n"
"\n"
"For concrete sets, two lemmas are often enough:\n"
"\n"
"- §10 — a singleton set is finite.\n"
"- §11 — inserting\n"
"  an element preserves finiteness (in both directions).\n"
"\n"
"There is also a convenience lemma:\n"
"- §12 — if Lean can automatically\n"
"  see the set is finite, §13 gives you a proof.\n"
"\n"
"## Your task\n"
"\n"
"Prove that the set §14 of natural numbers is finite.\n"
"\n"
"Recall that §15 is notation for §16.\n"
"So you can strip away elements one at a time with §17,\n"
"then finish with §18.\n"
"\n"
"Alternatively, §19 lets Lean figure it out automatically."
msgstr ""

