#: Game.Levels.FinsetExploration.L04_ImageUnderSquaring
msgid "You proved that squaring {1, 2, 3, 4, 5} gives {1, 4, 9, 16, 25}.\n"
"\n"
"The proof had two directions:\n"
"- **Forward**: Given a witness §0 with §1, case-split\n"
"  on which element §2 is and compute the square.\n"
"- **Backward**: Given §3, provide the square root\n"
"  as a witness.\n"
"\n"
"## Squaring is injective here\n"
"\n"
"Notice that all five squares are distinct: 1, 4, 9, 16, 25. This is\n"
"because §4 is injective on positive natural numbers. If we had\n"
"included negative numbers (in §5), we would see collisions:\n"
"§6.\n"
"\n"
"## Contrast with filter\n"
"\n"
"| Operation | Membership proof shape |\n"
"|-----------|----------------------|\n"
"| §7 | Conjunction: §8 |\n"
"| §9 | Existential: §10 |\n"
"\n"
"Filtering checks a property. Image requires a **witness** -- an element\n"
"that maps to the target.\n"
"\n"
"**In plain language**: \"Squaring each element of {1, 2, 3, 4, 5} gives\n"
"{1, 4, 9, 16, 25}. Each output has a unique preimage in the original set.\""
msgstr ""

