#: Game.Levels.FinThreeExamples.L04_Injectivity
msgid "# Proving Injectivity by Exhaustion\n"
"\n"
"A function §0 is **injective** if different inputs always\n"
"produce different outputs: whenever §1, we must have §2.\n"
"\n"
"In Lean, §3 unfolds to §4.\n"
"\n"
"For functions on small finite types, we can prove injectivity by\n"
"checking every pair of inputs. If §5, there are\n"
"only §6 pairs to consider.\n"
"\n"
"## The function\n"
"\n"
"Consider the \"cyclic shift\" on §7, defined as a lookup table:\n"
"§8\n"
"\n"
"This shifts every element forward by one (wrapping around). Since the\n"
"three outputs §9, §10, §11 are all distinct, the function is injective.\n"
"\n"
"## Your task\n"
"\n"
"Prove that this function is injective. After §12, use\n"
"§13 to enumerate all 9 pairs. In each case,\n"
"§14 is a concrete equation between §15 elements.\n"
"\n"
"For the 3 diagonal cases (where §16), the goal §17 follows\n"
"by §18. For the 6 off-diagonal cases (where §19), the hypothesis\n"
"§20 is a false equation (like §21), so you can derive §22.\n"
"\n"
"The pattern for the contradictory cases:\n"
"§23\n"
"\n"
"This extracts the value-level equation from §24 and lets §25\n"
"find the arithmetic contradiction."
msgstr ""

