#: Game.Levels.ThreeFiniteness.L03_FinsetContrast
msgid "# §0 vs §1 vs §2\n"
"\n"
"You now know two notions of finiteness:\n"
"- §3 — a predicate saying a set is finite.\n"
"- §4 — a type class saying a type is finite.\n"
"\n"
"The third notion is §5, which you have been using since early in\n"
"this course. A §6 is not a predicate or a type class — it is a\n"
"**data structure**: a concrete, computable collection of distinct elements.\n"
"\n"
"## Comparison\n"
"\n"
"| | §7 | §8 | §9 |\n"
"|---|---|---|---|\n"
"| **What is it** | Predicate | Type class | Data type |\n"
"| **Lives in** | §10 | instance system | a term |\n"
"| **Data** | none | §11 | the elements themselves |\n"
"| **Computable** | no | partially | yes |\n"
"\n"
"## The bridge: §12\n"
"\n"
"Every §13 can be coerced to a §14. Since a §15 has finitely\n"
"many elements by construction, this coerced set is always finite:\n"
"\n"
"§16\n"
"\n"
"This bridges §17 back to §18: if you have a concrete\n"
"finset, its underlying set is automatically §19.\n"
"\n"
"## Your task\n"
"\n"
"Prove that the coercion of the finset §20 to a set is §21."
msgstr ""

